    "summary": "The Colossus of Rhodes (c. 292–226 BC) was a gigantic bronze statue of the sun god Helios erected at the entrance to the harbor of Rhodes, commemorating the island city-state's successful defense against a siege by Demetrius Poliorcetes in 305 BC — the Rhodians sold the siege equipment left behind to fund the statue. Standing approximately 33 meters (108 feet) tall, it was counted among the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.\n\nRhodes was a prosperous independent city-state and the dominant naval power of the eastern Mediterranean during the early [[event:80|Hellenistic Period]], serving as a vital commercial hub connecting the Aegean, Egypt, and the Near East. The statue was constructed by the sculptor Chares of Lindos over twelve years and represented the pinnacle of Hellenistic bronze-casting technology. Contrary to popular medieval and modern belief, ancient sources do not claim that it straddled the harbor entrance — it almost certainly stood on one side of the harbor mouth. It was destroyed by an earthquake around 226 BC; the bronze fragments reportedly remained on the ground for nearly 900 years before Arab invaders finally removed and sold them in 654 AD.",
